<Author>Gwyndy
<Content>Very good My wife and I stayed at the City Inn for a couple of nights in February 2008.The hotel is everything that other reviewers have already said - great location, quiet, pleasant and helpful staff and, with a couple of small exceptions, very good service.The door of our taxi was opened almost before it stopped moving. We were greeted by a delightful young man and escorted to the reception desk where we were speedily checked in by a very charming and efficient young lady. Our standard room was quite acceptable. It was a very standard modern box but what it lacked in architectural charm it made up for in amenities - small flat screen TV with plenty of channels, DVD player, separate mini hi-fi system, mini bar, tea / coffee making facilities with good ground coffee bags and a sensible supply of milk, hair dryer, ironing board and iron. There is also a free DVD / CD loan facility available from the concierge. The bathroom was small - shower only - but more than adequate.The Millbank Lounge was a pleasant area to sit and have a drink. Breakfast in the City Cafe was very good - everything from the healthy continental style buffet to the artery-clogging full English! The City Cafe is also open for lunch and dinner. Although we did not eat there other than breakfast, the menus look interesting and not over priced.We did have a couple of issues with service at breakfast on the second morning and when trying to get coffee in the Millbank lounge one afternoon but I am sure that these were not typical of normal operations in this hotel. When I mentioned these points via the hotel's on-line feedback facility I received a very rapid response and apology from the hotel's General Manager and an assurance that the matters would be addressed. I have every confidence that they will be. This is obviously a hotel that prides itself on the quality of it's service and that is determined not to let even minor glitches detract from it's very high standards.I would take issue with the hotel's Best Rate Guarantee policy which promises to match any publicly available price for rooms. I was about to book direct with the hotel at a price of around 拢375 for two nights BB. Via Tripadvisor I found a price of 拢226 on www.otel.com. Having never used any of these internet hotel booking sites before, I 'phoned the hotel and asked if they would match the price but they would not do so. Apparently one has to book with the hotel and then submit a claim within 24 hours of booking. I think that this is pointless. Anyway I booked with otel.com and had no problems.Judging from the reviews posted on Tripadvisor, London must be awash with over-priced and badly serviced hotels. The City Inn is certainly not one of them. We don't visit London very often but next time we do so The City Inn will most certainly be our first choice hotel. 
