<Content>State of the art hotel beside the Tate Britain Gallery This is a recently built hotel with all of the modern design touches (including flat screen television, ergonomic power shower and bed made in heaven) which make the bedrooms very comfortable. Having paid a reasonable Euro 177 all in for the room, I stayed at City Inn on the night of the 20th of December. I was famished after my jouney and ordered the Suffolk pork belly with stir fry vegetables + a beer for circa 拢20 through room service. The food was really delicious and the same was true of the cooked breakfast which they delivered to the room, together with a complimentary Financial Times, the following day. Check in staff were warm and welcoming. And, when my television went on the blink, they sent someone to fix it within five minutes. The hotel itself is a good place to be, with a large and lively lobby and a busy bar and restaurant. Sadly, I was not allocated a riverview room. But I think they give these rooms to their regular customers. Which is only fair, in all the circumstances.The location is a little off the beaten track. If not travelling by taxi, you can get there via Pimlico tube on the Victoria line. When you exit the tube station, you follow the signs for the Tate Britain gallery. You turn right onto Vauxhall Bridge Road and follow it for a couple of hundred metres until you reach John Islip Street. You follow this long winding street for about 600 metres until you reach the City Inn (which is literally a hundred metres up the road from Tate Britain). As you walk towards the hotel, you will see Labour Party HQ at Millbank as a landmark on your right hand side. Just stayed here for one night because the Sofitel St James were offering rooms at Euro 199 a night for the nights of the 21st and 22nd of December. Although the City Inn is not quite in the same league as the five star Sofitel, it was still a very relaxing place in which to spend the evening of the 20th of December last. 
